Tesla Solar Reviews, Services and Costs (2024)

Last Updated: Nov 15, 2024
Tesla Solar offers a combination of high-quality equipment and affordable pricing, based on the MarketWatch Guides teams review. The companys in-house solar panels and batteries are some of the most popular solar products on the market. Our team conducted a 2023 Pollfish of 1,000 solar customers in which Tesla ranked as the third most popular choice for solar services, with 13.5% of respondents choosing the company.

Our Thoughts on Tesla Solar

Tesla Solar is a sound option for people who want an installer that offers an integrated product ecosystem, including solar panels, inverters, batteries and electric vehicles (EV) and charging. Tesla has reliable products and eye-catching designs its all-black solar panels with rail-less, concealed edge mounting create sleek solar power systems. Customers can also opt for a solar roof, which will cost more than traditional panels.  

With more than half a million systems installed, according to its website, Tesla Solar has the experience to prove its value. It also guarantees the lowest price in America, thanks to a price-match guarantee. These factors make Tesla Energy one of our picks for the best solar companies in North America.

Tesla Solar State Availability

Tesla Solar serves all 50 U.S. states and is available in most cities and towns. However, Tesla does not use in-house employees for all of its system installations. The company relies on authorized partners that install Tesla equipment across the country.

For a typical 8 kilowatt (kW) system, homeowners choosing Tesla can expect to spend about $2.10 to $2.85 per watt. This rate translates to a range of $16,000 to $23,000 before any tax incentives, credits and rebates apply. The following table shows estimated pricing for a variety of Tesla solar systems.

Marketwatch Guides Tip

Tesla Solar is among the cheaper options for solar panel installations based on companies weve reviewed. The company typically charges $2.10 to $2.85 per watt, compared to the national average of $2.85. Moreover, the company offers a price match guarantee to help ensure low pricing.

Solar Panel Brands Offered

One of the things that sets Tesla Energy apart from some other installers is that it manufactures most of its solar equipment in-house, including solar panels, inverters and the Powerwall battery.

Although Tesla Solar limits the number of equipment choices for customers, its products offer high performance and durability with pleasing aesthetics. For instance, Tesla solar panels have an all-black design and are installed in a low-profile manner with all-black skirting to create a monochromatic, eye-catching system.

Page 1 of

For customers who want an even sleeker option, Tesla Solar has an innovative solar roof system that integrates solar cells into roof shingles, creating a nearly invisible solar array. However, this option is more expensive than traditional solar panels.

Solar Battery Installation

Another one of Tesla Solars selling points is the use of its own solar battery, the Powerwall. Unlike some other solar installers, Tesla designs and manufactures its own solar battery, bolstered by the companys experience building electric cars. The Powerwall is one of the top-rated solar batteries based on our teams review.

Our 2023 survey data highlights the Powerwalls popularity. Of the 59% of respondents who installed a solar battery with a solar panel system, nearly one-third reported that they picked a Powerwall.

Adding an energy storage system to an existing solar system may cost between $12,000 and $22,000. So in terms of pricing, a typical solar panel and battery system costs between $25,000 and $35,000. Additional Services

Tesla is a brand most often linked to electric vehicles, but the company also manufactures solar-related products. Here is a list of Teslas services and products:

  • EV charger installations
  • Mobile app 
  • Solar battery manufacturing and installation
  • Solar panel manufacturing and installation
  • Solar roofing 

Payment Options

Tesla Energy provides a variety of payment options for solar customers. Buyers can pay in cash, a method that does not accrue interest and as a result, translates to the highest amount of savings over a systems lifetime. 

Alternatively, customers can choose a solar loan, lease or power purchase agreement (PPA) to offset the upfront cost of solar. However, leases and PPAs deliver significantly lower savings than other options and you will never own the system. These payment methods also make the customer ineligible for the 30% federal tax credit. 

Tesla Solar Warranties

Solar warranties are an important factor to consider when considering a move to solar power. Tesla Solar offers a warranty structure that nearly matches the industry standard, covering panels for 25 years and system workmanship for 10 years.  

Page 1 of

Tesla Solar Installation Process

Tesla Solar has a four-step installation process, as outlined on its website. It involves the standard steps in a typical solar installation and is mostly similar to other solar companies weve reviewed.  

  1. Order online: The first step with Tesla differs from some other solar installers. Tesla Solar uses an online ordering system, unlike other companies that generally use human salespersons to reach out to homeowners. Interested homeowners can enter their address and monthly energy bill on Teslas website, and the installer will prepare an instant quote. Buyers can also choose to schedule a consultation with a company salesperson for a more traditional approach to going solar.
  2. Home assessment: Using aerial and satellite imagery, Teslas design engineers can create a system to meet your homes energy needs. You can provide preferences for your system layout using Teslas online system. Once Tesla finalizes your design, the company will work with your municipalities to apply for the necessary installation permits. 
  3. Installation: Once Tesla receives the necessary permits, the company lets customers choose an installation date. According to Tesla, you only need to be home during the first hour of installation. Upon completion of the installation, Tesla works with the local building department and the utility company to arrange for system inspections and receive a permission-to-operate (PTO) certificate.
  4. Power on: After receiving PTO, Tesla notifies the user when it is safe to switch the system on and then it flips the switch.

What Customers Think of Tesla Solar

To get an idea of what customers like and dislike about Teslas solar division, our team read through reviews on the Better Business Bureau and Trustpilot. The company also has a separate review page for its overall operations, which include solar technology. While the company has several positive customer reviews, it also receives a considerable number of negative reviews. 

What Customers Like

  • Ordering process: Many customers praise Teslas online ordering system, which suggests an approximate system size and configuration while also preparing preliminary pricing without having to interact with a salesperson. 
  • Product quality: Reviewers often highlight the companys high-quality solar equipment as a reason to choose Tesla Solar, including its all-black solar panels.
  • Knowledgeable salespersons: Numerous Tesla customers mentioned having a pleasant experience dealing with the companys sales representatives, who they described as professional, knowledgeable and responsive. 

What Customers Dont Like

  • Slow support: Many reviewers noted Teslas slow technical support group, especially related to component repair or replacement. Some customers also mentioned a slow installation speed.

Our team reached out to Tesla for comment on the above-listed negative review but did not receive a response.

Tesla Solar vs. the Market

Our team compared how Tesla Energy measures up against ADT Solar and Sunrun, two of its major competitors in the U.S. market.

When you compare Tesla versus ADT Solar or Sunrun, the most noticeable differences are Teslas wider array of services and its in-house product offerings. Another distinguishing factor is Teslas relatively low pricing, which may drop to as low as $10,000 less than the other two companies.

Frequently Asked Questions About Tesla Solar

Tesla manufactures its own solar panels and other equipment, including batteries. The company also manufactures and offers solar shingles for those interested in a solar roof system.

Teslas solar battery, the Powerwall, has a life expectancy of at least 10 years. The battery also comes with a 10-year warranty to cover manufacturing issues over that time.

Based on our research, an 8 kW solar system costs $16,000 to $23,000 with Tesla. Teslas solar panels are not as expensive as some other options, making its solar systems some of the most affordable systems on the market.
